data.summary: [at Barrons.com] - Shares of chip equipment maker Axcelis Technologies (ACLS) today closed down 25 cents, or 1.6%, at $15.30, after the company this morning said it got new orders for its “Purion H” tools, which are used to make memory chips. Needham & Co.’s Edwin Mok thinks that’s significant for the company, and puts it on the road to recovery in 2017, based on a ramp in spending to make “3D” NAND chips and also DRAM. Said Axcelis, “the systems will be used to support capacity ramps for next generation memory products,” adding that the machines will ship "in the first quarter." Mok, who has a Buy rating on Axcelis shares, and an $18 price target, writes that "ACLS is finally regaining momentum with its Purion platform, particularly in memory following spending delays in 3Q16." "Based on near-term strength in both 3D NAND and DRAM investments, we see a strong C1H17 for ACLS." Mok details his expectations: With the return of Purion momentum especially within memory, an area of strength for ACLS, we believe ACLS will deliver better than expected 1H17 performance.
data.title: Axcelis Can Ride Ramp in 3-D NAND, DRAM Chips, Says Needham
